    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="534"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/1006.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Blanchard</persName>, to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 29, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>General uprising here last night, heavy firing all over the city. The capital in
                    complete possession of the revolution. The members of the Government refugees in
                    the various legations and consulates. President Zamor fled and he is on board
                    Dutch vessel which passed here last night from Gonaives to Petit Goave and which
                    is expected to return this afternoon when the President’s wife and child, and
                        <pb facs="0471" n="355" xml:id="pg_355"/> General Charles Zamor, Minister of
                    the Interior, propose to embark under the protection of Dominican Legation where
                    they are now refugees. Firing still continues; much excitement and disorder,
                    there being no constituted authority. Executive palace looted, general pillage
                    and incendiarism feared. Presence of war vessels urgent.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Blanchard</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
